
[1]countersign

   COUNTERSIGN, v.t. [counter and sign.] Literally, to sign on the
   opposite side of an instrument or writing; hence, to sign, as secretary
   or other subordinate officer, a writing signed by a principal or
   superior, to attest the authenticity of the writing. Thus charters
   signed by a king are countersigned by a secretary. Bank notes signed by
   the president are countersigned by the cashier.

   COUNTERSIGN, n. A private signal, word or phrase, given to soldiers on
   guard, with orders to let no man pass unless he first names that sign;
   a military watchword. Advance and give the countersign.
